The **Denver Broncos** are a professional [American football](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_football) team based in [Denver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver). The Broncos compete in the [National Football League](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League) (NFL) as a member of the [American Football Conference](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_Conference) (AFC) [West](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFC_West) division. The team is headquartered in [Englewood, Colorado](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Englewood,_Colorado).[\[3\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-DenverBroncosContact-3)[\[4\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroncosPark-4)

The team began play in 1960 as a charter member of the [American Football League](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_League) (AFL) and joined the NFL as part of the [merger](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFL%E2%80%93NFL_merger) in 1970\. The Broncos are currently owned by the [Walton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S._Robson_Walton)\-[Penner](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greg_Penner) group. Since 2001, the Broncos have played their regular season home games at [Empower Field at Mile High](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empower_Field_at_Mile_High); Denver previously played its home games at [Mile High Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile_High_Stadium) from its inception in 1960 through the 2000 season.

The Broncos were barely competitive during their 10-year run in the AFL and their first three years in the NFL. They did not have a winning season until [1973](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1973_Denver_Broncos_season) and qualified for their first playoffs in [1977](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1977_Denver_Broncos_season), eventually advancing to [Super Bowl XII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XII) that season. From 1973 to 2016, the Broncos suffered only eleven losing seasons and won 3 Super Bowls, becoming one of the NFL's most successful teams.[\[8\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-9) They have won eight [AFC Championships](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFC_Championship_Game) ([1977](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1977_NFL_season), [1986](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1986_NFL_season), [1987](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1987_NFL_season), [1989](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989_NFL_season), [1997](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_NFL_season), [1998](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_NFL_season), [2013](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_NFL_season), [2015](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_NFL_season)), and three [Super Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Super_Bowl_champions) championships ([1997](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_NFL_season) ([XXXII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXII)), [1998](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_NFL_season) ([XXXIII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXIII)), [2015](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_NFL_season) ([50](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_50)), and share the NFL record for most Super Bowl losses (5 – tied with the [New England Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_England_Patriots)). The Broncos have nine primary members enshrined in the [Pro Football Hall of Fame](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro_Football_Hall_of_Fame): [John Elway](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Elway), [Floyd Little](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floyd_Little), [Shannon Sharpe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_Sharpe), [Gary Zimmerman](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gary_Zimmerman), [Terrell Davis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terrell_Davis), [Champ Bailey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Champ_Bailey), [Steve Atwater](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Atwater), and [Randy Gradishar](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Randy_Gradishar), along with late club owner [Pat Bowlen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pat_Bowlen).[\[9\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-10)

According to [*Forbes*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forbes), the Broncos are valued at $4.65 billion in July 2022 making them the twelfth most-valuable team in the NFL.[\[10\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-11)

**History**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=1)\]

*Further information: [History of the Denver Broncos](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_Denver_Broncos)*

**Bob Howsam/Gerald Phipps era (1960–1980)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=2)\]

The Denver Broncos were founded on August 14, 1959, when [minor league](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minor_League_Baseball) baseball owner [Bob Howsam](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Howsam) was awarded an [American Football League](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_League) (AFL) charter franchise.[\[2\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-ProFootballHOF1-2) The Broncos won the first-ever AFL game over the [Boston Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1960_Boston_Patriots_season) 13–10, on September 9, [1960](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1960_Denver_Broncos_season). Seven years later on August 5, [1967](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1967_AFL_season), they became the first-ever AFL team to defeat an [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League) team, with a 13–7 win over the [Detroit Lions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1967_Detroit_Lions_season) in a preseason game.[\[2\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-ProFootballHOF1-2) However, the Broncos were not successful in the 1960s, winning more than five games only once (7–7, [1962](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1962_Denver_Broncos_season)), compiling a 39–97–4 (.293) record during the ten seasons of the AFL.[\[11\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-12)

Denver came close to losing its franchise in [1965](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1965_Denver_Broncos_season), until a local ownership group took control,[\[12\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-shftm-13)[\[13\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-brsold65-14) and rebuilt the team.[\[14\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-15) The team's first superstar, "Franchise" [Floyd Little](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Floyd_Little), was instrumental in keeping the team in Denver, due to his signing in [1967](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1967_Denver_Broncos_season) as well as his [Pro Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro_Bowl) efforts on and off the field. The Broncos were the only original AFL team that never played in the title game, as well as the only original AFL team never to have a winning season while a member of the AFL during the upstart league's 10-year history.[\[15\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-16)

In 1972, the Broncos hired former [Stanford University](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanford_Cardinal_football) coach [John Ralston](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Ralston_\(coach\)) as their [head coach](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_head_coaches).[\[16\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-l128-17) In [1973](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1973_Denver_Broncos_season), he was the [UPI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_Press_International)'s [AFC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_Conference) Coach of the Year, after Denver achieved its first winning season at 7–5–2. In five seasons with the Broncos, Ralston guided the team to three winning seasons. Though Ralston finished the [1976 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1976_Denver_Broncos_season) with a 9–5 record, the team, as was the case in Ralston's previous winning seasons, still missed the playoffs. Following the season, several prominent players publicly voiced their discontent with Ralston, which soon led to his resignation.[\[17\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroncosSportsE-Cyclopedia-18)

![][image6]

The Broncos defeated the Raiders in the [1977–78](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1977%E2%80%9378_NFL_playoffs) AFC Championship Game to earn their first trip to the Super Bowl.

[Red Miller](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Red_Miller), a long-time assistant coach, was hired and along with the [Orange Crush Defense](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orange_Crush_Defense) (a nickname originated in 1977, also the brand of [the popular orange-flavored soft drink](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orange_Crush)) and aging [quarterback](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_starting_quarterbacks) [Craig Morton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Craig_Morton), took the Broncos to what was then a record-setting 12–2 regular-season record and their first playoff appearance in [1977](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1977_Denver_Broncos_season), and ultimately made their first Super Bowl appearance in [Super Bowl XII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XII), in which they were defeated by the [Dallas Cowboys](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1977_Dallas_Cowboys_season) (Morton's former team), 27–10.[\[18\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-19)

**Edgar Kaiser/Pat Bowlen era (1981–2018)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=3)\]

In [1981](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1981_Denver_Broncos_season), Broncos' owner [Gerald Phipps](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerald_Phipps), who had purchased the team in May 1961 from the original owner [Bob Howsam](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bob_Howsam), sold the team to Canadian financier [Edgar Kaiser Jr.](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Edgar_Kaiser_Jr.), grandson of shipbuilding industrialist [Henry J. Kaiser](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry_J._Kaiser).[\[19\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-20) In [1984](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1984_Denver_Broncos_season), the team was purchased by another Canadian, [Pat Bowlen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pat_Bowlen), who placed team ownership into a family trust sometime before [2004](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2004_Denver_Broncos_season) and remained in day-to-day control until his battle with [Alzheimer's disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alzheimer%27s_disease) forced him to cede the team to [Joe Ellis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Ellis) in [2014](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_Denver_Broncos_season).[\[20\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BowlenSteppingBack-21)[\[21\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroncosOwner-22)[\[22\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-Klis,_Mike-23)

**Dan Reeves years (1981–1992)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=4)\]

[Dan Reeves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_Reeves) became the youngest head coach (37) in the [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League) when he joined the Broncos in [1981](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1981_Denver_Broncos_season) as vice president and [head coach](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_head_coaches). [Quarterback](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_starting_quarterbacks) [John Elway](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Elway), who played college football at [Stanford](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stanford_Cardinal_football), arrived in [1983](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1983_Denver_Broncos_season) via a trade. Originally drafted by the [Baltimore Colts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baltimore_Colts) as the first pick of the [draft](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1983_NFL_draft), Elway proclaimed that he would shun football in favor of [baseball](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Major_League_Baseball) (he was drafted by the [New York Yankees](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_York_Yankees) to play [center field](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Center_fielder) and was also a pitching prospect), unless he was traded to a selected list of other teams, which included the Broncos.[\[23\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-24) Prior to Elway, the Broncos had over 24 different starting quarterbacks in its 23 seasons to that point.[\[24\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-25)

![][image7]

A ticket for the [1987–88 AFC Championship Game](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1987%E2%80%9388_NFL_playoffs) between the Browns and the Broncos.

![][image8]

John Elway (*right*) hands the ball for a rushing play against the Packers in 1984\.

Reeves and Elway guided the Broncos to six post-season appearances, five [AFC West](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFC_West) divisional titles, three [AFC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_Conference) championships and three [Super Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl) appearances (Super Bowl XXI, XXII and XXIV) during their 12-year span together. The Broncos lost [Super Bowl XXI](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXI) to the [New York Giants](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1986_New_York_Giants_season), 39–20; [Super Bowl XXII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXII) to the [Washington Redskins](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1987_Washington_Redskins_season), 42–10; and [Super Bowl XXIV](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXIV) to the [San Francisco 49ers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989_San_Francisco_49ers_season), 55–10; the latter score remains the most lopsided scoring differential in Super Bowl history.[\[25\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-26) The last year of the Reeves-Elway era were marked by feuding, due to Reeves taking on play-calling duties after ousting Elway's favorite offensive coordinator [Mike Shanahan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Shanahan) after the [1991 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1991_Denver_Broncos_season), as well as Reeves drafting quarterback [Tommy Maddox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tommy_Maddox) out of [UCLA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/UCLA_Bruins_football) instead of going with a [wide receiver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wide_receiver) to help Elway. Reeves was fired after the [1992 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1992_Denver_Broncos_season) and replaced by his protégé and friend [Wade Phillips](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wade_Phillips), who had been serving as the Broncos' defensive coordinator.[\[26\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-27)[\[27\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-28)[\[28\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-sportsillustrated.cnn.com-29) Phillips was fired after a mediocre [1994 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1994_Denver_Broncos_season), in which management felt he lost control of the team.[\[29\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-i392-30)

**Mike Shanahan years (1995–2008)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=5)\]

In [1995](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1995_Denver_Broncos_season), [Mike Shanahan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Shanahan), who had formerly served under Reeves as the Broncos' offensive coordinator, returned as head coach.[\[30\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-l030-31) The team went 8–8 in 1995\.[\[31\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-32) Shanahan drafted rookie [running back](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Running_back) [Terrell Davis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terrell_Davis). In [1996](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1996_Denver_Broncos_season), the Broncos were the top seed in the AFC with a 13–3 record, dominating most of the teams that year. The fifth-seeded [Jacksonville Jaguars](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1996_Jacksonville_Jaguars_season), however, upset the Broncos 30–27 in the divisional round of the playoffs, ending the Broncos' 1996 run.[\[32\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-33)[\[33\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-34)

**Super Bowl XXXII champions (1997)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=6)\]

During the [1997 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Denver_Broncos_season), Elway and Davis helped guide the Broncos to their first Super Bowl victory, a 31–24 win over the defending champion [Green Bay Packers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Green_Bay_Packers_season) in [Super Bowl XXXII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXII). Though Elway completed only 13 of 22 passes, throwing one interception and no touchdowns (he did, however, have a rushing touchdown), Davis rushed for 157 yards and a Super Bowl-record three touchdowns to earn the [Super Bowl Most Valuable Player Award](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_Most_Valuable_Player_Award)—this while overcoming a severe migraine headache that caused him blurred vision.[\[34\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-35)[\[35\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-w888-36)

**Super Bowl XXXIII champions (1998)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=7)\]

The Broncos repeated as Super Bowl champions the following season, defeating the [Atlanta Falcons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_Atlanta_Falcons_season) (led by Elway's longtime head coach [Dan Reeves](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dan_Reeves)) in [Super Bowl XXXIII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXIII), 34–19. Elway was named Super Bowl MVP, completing 18 of 29 passes for 336 yards, with an 80-yard touchdown to wide receiver [Rod Smith](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rod_Smith_\(wide_receiver\)) and one interception.[\[36\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-37)

![][image9]

Broncos' quarterback [Jay Cutler](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Cutler) in 2007\.

John Elway retired following the [1998 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_Denver_Broncos_season), and [Brian Griese](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Griese) started at [quarterback](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_starting_quarterbacks) for the next four seasons. After a 6–10 record in [1999](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1999_Denver_Broncos_season), mostly due to a season-ending injury to Terrell Davis, the Broncos recovered in [2000](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2000_Denver_Broncos_season), earning a Wild Card playoff berth, but losing to the eventual [Super Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXV) champion [Baltimore Ravens](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2000_Baltimore_Ravens_season).[\[37\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-38)[\[38\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-39) After missing the playoffs the following two seasons,[\[39\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-40)[\[40\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-41) former [Arizona Cardinals](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arizona_Cardinals)' quarterback [Jake Plummer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jake_Plummer) replaced Griese in [2003](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2003_Denver_Broncos_season), and led the Broncos to two straight 10–6 seasons, earning Wild Card playoff berths both years.[\[41\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-42)[\[42\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-43) However, the Broncos went on the road to face the [Indianapolis Colts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indianapolis_Colts) in back-to-back seasons and were blown out by more than 20 points in each game, allowing a combined 90 points.[\[17\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroncosSportsE-Cyclopedia-18)

In the years following the back-to-back championships, a league investigation found that the team had circumvented the salary cap in both seasons and the 1996 season by deferring additional money to Elway and Davis outside of the salary cap. In addition, they purposefully avoided waiving certain players before a certain date. Denver claimed the moves did not give them additional competitive advantage. The NFL gave no formal statement, although between two separate punishments stripped the team of their third-round picks in the [2002](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2002_NFL_draft) and [2005](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2005_NFL_draft) drafts and fined them nearly $2 million combined.[\[43\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-e469-44)[\[44\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-45)

Plummer led the Broncos to a 13–3 record in [2005](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2005_Denver_Broncos_season) and their first [AFC West](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFC_West) division title since 1998\.[\[45\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-46) After a first-round [bye](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bye_\(sports\)), the Broncos defeated the defending Super Bowl champion [New England Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2005_New_England_Patriots_season), 27–13, denying New England from becoming the first [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League) team ever to win three consecutive Super Bowl championships.[\[46\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-47) They were the first team to beat the Patriots in the playoffs during the Tom Brady era. The Broncos' playoff run came to an end the next week, after losing at home to the [Pittsburgh Steelers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2005_Pittsburgh_Steelers_season) in the AFC Championship game, 34–17.[\[47\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-48)

The Broncos' defense began the first five games of the [2006 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006_Denver_Broncos_season) allowing only one touchdown — an NFL record that still stands. ESPN commentator and Super Bowl-winning quarterback Joe Theismann gave the 2006 defense the name "Bad Blue" on [*Monday Night Football*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monday_Night_Football) as they played the Ravens. However, the team struggled down the season stretch. Plummer led the team to a 7–2 record, but struggled individually with inconsistent performance and more interceptions than touchdown passes. As a result, he would be replaced by rookie quarterback [Jay Cutler](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jay_Cutler). Cutler went 2–3 as a starter, and the Broncos finished with a 9–7 record, losing the tiebreaker to the [Kansas City Chiefs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2006_Kansas_City_Chiefs_season) for the final playoff spot.[\[48\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-49) Cutler's first full season as a starter in [2007](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_Denver_Broncos_season) became the Broncos' first losing season since 1999, with a 7–9 record.[\[49\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-50)

The [2008 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008_Denver_Broncos_season) ended in a 52–21 loss at the [San Diego Chargers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008_San_Diego_Chargers_season), giving the Broncos an 8–8 record and their third straight season out of the playoffs.[\[50\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-51) [Mike Shanahan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Shanahan), the longest-tenured and most successful [head coach](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_head_coaches) in Broncos' franchise history, was fired after 14 seasons.[\[51\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-52)

**Josh McDaniels years (2009–2010)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=8)\]

On January 11, 2009, two weeks after Shanahan was fired, the Broncos hired former New England Patriots' offensive coordinator [Josh McDaniels](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josh_McDaniels) as the team's new head coach.[\[52\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-53) Three months later, the team acquired quarterback [Kyle Orton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyle_Orton) as part of a trade that sent Jay Cutler to the [Chicago Bears](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_Bears).[\[53\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-54)

Under McDaniels and Orton, the Broncos jumped out to a surprising 6–0 start in [2009](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_Denver_Broncos_season). However, the team lost eight of their next ten games, finishing 8–8 for a second consecutive season and missing the playoffs.[\[54\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-55) The next season ([2010](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_Denver_Broncos_season)), the Broncos set a new franchise record for losses in a single season, with a 4–12 record.[\[55\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-56) McDaniels was fired before the end of the 2010 season following a combination of the team's poor record and the fallout from a highly publicized [videotaping scandal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steve_Scarnecchia).[\[56\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-u854-57) Running backs coach [Eric Studesville](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Studesville) was named interim coach for the final four games of the 2010 season.[\[57\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-58) He chose to start rookie first-round draft choice [Tim Tebow](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Tebow) at quarterback for the final three games.[\[58\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-59)

**John Fox years (2011–2014)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=9)\]

Following the [2010 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2010_Denver_Broncos_season), [Joe Ellis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Ellis) was promoted from chief operating officer to team president, while [John Elway](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Elway) returned to the organization as the team's executive vice president of football operations.[\[59\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-60) In addition, the Broncos hired [John Fox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Fox_\(American_football\)) as the team's 14th [head coach](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_head_coaches). Fox previously served as the [Carolina Panthers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carolina_Panthers)' head coach from 2002 to 2010\.[\[60\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-61)

Following a 1–4 start to the [2011 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_Denver_Broncos_season), [Tim Tebow](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Tebow) replaced [Kyle Orton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyle_Orton) as the Broncos' starting [quarterback](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_starting_quarterbacks), and "Tebow Time" was born.[\[61\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-62) Tebow led the Broncos with toughness, determination and miraculous come-from-behind victories which gave the Broncos hope and were the catalyst for better things to come. Tebow led the Broncos to an 8–8 record and garnered the team's first playoff berth and division title since [2005](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2005_Denver_Broncos_season). The Broncos defeated the Pittsburgh Steelers in the Wild Card round on a memorable 80-yard touchdown pass from Tebow to [wide receiver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wide_receiver) [Demaryius Thomas](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demaryius_Thomas) on the first play of overtime, setting a record for the fastest overtime in [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League) history.[\[62\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-63) However, the Broncos lost to the [New England Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_New_England_Patriots_season) in the Divisional round.[\[63\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroncosPatriots2011-64)

In March 2012, the Broncos reached an agreement on a five-year, [$](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar)96 million contract with former longtime [Indianapolis Colts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indianapolis_Colts)' quarterback [Peyton Manning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peyton_Manning), who had recently missed the entire [2011](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_NFL_season) season following multiple neck surgeries.[\[64\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-65)[\[65\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-66) This resulted in the Broncos subsequently trading incumbent quarterback Tim Tebow to the [New York Jets](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_New_York_Jets_season).[\[66\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-67) The Broncos finished with a 13–3 record and the [AFC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_Conference)'s No. 1 seed in the [2012 playoffs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012%E2%80%9313_NFL_playoffs), but were [defeated by the Baltimore Ravens](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile_High_Miracle) in the Divisional round.[\[67\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-68)

Like in [2012](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_Denver_Broncos_season), the [2013 Broncos](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_Denver_Broncos_season) finished with a 13–3 record and the AFC's No. 1 seed.[\[68\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-69) The Broncos broke all offensive records and QB Peyton Manning shattered many quarterback records that season as well.[\[69\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-e573-70) In the [2013 playoffs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013%E2%80%9314_NFL_playoffs), they defeated the [San Diego Chargers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_San_Diego_Chargers_season) in the Divisional round and the [New England Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_New_England_Patriots_season) in the AFC Championship.[\[70\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-z759-71)[\[71\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-d003-72) However, the Broncos lost to the [Seattle Seahawks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_Seattle_Seahawks_season) in [Super Bowl XLVIII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XLVIII) by a score of 43–8, the Broncos' first [Super Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl) berth since winning back-to-back Super Bowls in [1997](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Denver_Broncos_season) and [1998](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_Denver_Broncos_season).[\[72\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-73)

Prior to the start of the [2014 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_Denver_Broncos_season), the Broncos announced that [Pat Bowlen](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pat_Bowlen), the team's owner since [1984](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1984_Denver_Broncos_season), relinquished control of the team due to his battle with [Alzheimer's disease](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alzheimer%27s_disease), resulting in team president Joe Ellis and general manager John Elway assuming control of the team.[\[22\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-Klis,_Mike-23) The Broncos finished the 2014 season with a 12–4 record and the AFC's No. 2 seed.[\[73\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-74) However, the Broncos were defeated by the [Indianapolis Colts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014_Indianapolis_Colts_season) in the Divisional round of the [2014 playoffs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2014%E2%80%9315_NFL_playoffs), marking the third time in four seasons that the Broncos lost in the Divisional round of the playoffs.[\[74\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-o604-75) Quarterback Peyton Manning had been playing with strained quadriceps for the final month of the 2014 season.[\[75\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-76)

![][image10]

[Gary Kubiak](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gary_Kubiak) won [Super Bowl 50](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_50) in his first season as the Broncos head coach.

**Gary Kubiak years (2015–2016)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=10)\]

On January 12, 2015, one day after the divisional playoff loss to the Colts, the Broncos and [head coach](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_head_coaches) [John Fox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Fox_\(American_football\)) mutually agreed to part ways.[\[76\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-77) Fox left the Broncos with a .719 winning percentage in his four seasons as the Broncos' head coach—the highest in franchise history.[\[77\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-78) One week later, the Broncos hired [Gary Kubiak](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gary_Kubiak) as the team's 15th head coach.[\[78\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-79) Kubiak served as a backup quarterback to executive vice president/general manager John Elway from 1983 to 1991, as well as the Broncos' offensive coordinator from 1995 to 2005\.[\[79\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-80)

Shortly after Kubiak became head coach, the Broncos underwent numerous changes to their coaching staff and players, including the hiring of defensive coordinator, defensive mastermind [Wade Phillips](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wade_Phillips), under whom the Broncos' defense went from middle of the road to being ranked No. 1 in the NFL. By the [2015 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_Denver_Broncos_season), it would go on to be considered one of the greatest NFL defenses of all time — along with the 1985 Bears, 2000 Ravens and 2002 Buccaneers.[\[80\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-v687-81) The Broncos finished with a 12–4 record and the AFC's No. 1 seed, despite [Peyton Manning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peyton_Manning) having his worst statistical season since his rookie year with the [Indianapolis Colts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indianapolis_Colts) in [1998](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_NFL_season).[\[81\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-82) Backup quarterback [Brock Osweiler](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brock_Osweiler) started the last six games of the regular season due to Manning suffering from a foot injury.[\[82\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-i843-83) Manning led the Broncos throughout the [playoffs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015%E2%80%9316_NFL_playoffs). The Broncos defeated the [Pittsburgh Steelers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_Pittsburgh_Steelers_season) 23–16 in the Divisional Round and the [New England Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_New_England_Patriots_season) 20–18 in the AFC Championship.[\[83\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-o085-84)[\[84\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-e282-85) They were victorious against the [Carolina Panthers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_Carolina_Panthers_season) 24–10 in [Super Bowl 50](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_50) for their third Super Bowl title.[\[85\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-86)

On March 7, 2016, quarterback Peyton Manning retired after 18 NFL seasons during a press conference at the team's [Dove Valley](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dove_Valley,_Colorado) headquarters.[\[86\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-87)[\[87\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-88)

Following Manning's retirement, the Broncos scrambled to find the team's next starting quarterback after backup quarterback Brock Osweiler departed on a four-year contract to the [Houston Texans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Houston_Texans_season).[\[88\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-t831-89) The Broncos acquired [Mark Sanchez](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Sanchez) from the [Philadelphia Eagles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Philadelphia_Eagles_season) and selected [Paxton Lynch](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paxton_Lynch) during the [2016](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_NFL_draft) draft.[\[89\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-d940-90)[\[90\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-z129-91) Sanchez, Lynch and second-year quarterback [Trevor Siemian](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trevor_Siemian) competed for the starting quarterback spot during the off-season and preseason. Prior to the [regular season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_NFL_season), Sanchez was released and Siemian was named the starter.[\[91\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-z198-92)[\[92\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-o365-93) The Broncos finished the season 9–7 and missed the playoffs for the first time since 2010\.[\[93\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-a520-94)[\[94\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-95)

On January 2, 2017, coach Gary Kubiak announced his retirement, citing health as the main reason for retiring.[\[95\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-96)

**Vance Joseph years (2017–2018)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=11)\]

The Broncos hired [Miami Dolphins](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Miami_Dolphins) defensive coordinator [Vance Joseph](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vance_Joseph) as head coach on January 11, 2017\.[\[96\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-97) The Broncos finished 5–11 in 2017 as a result of an unimpressive offense led by a quarterback committee of [Trevor Siemian](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trevor_Siemian), [Brock Osweiler](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brock_Osweiler), and [Paxton Lynch](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paxton_Lynch).[\[97\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-98)

In an effort to address poor production from the offense, the Broncos signed quarterback [Case Keenum](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Case_Keenum) on March 14, 2018, and traded away Trevor Siemian to the [Minnesota Vikings](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minnesota_Vikings) on March 19, 2018\.[\[98\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-u928-99)[\[99\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-r762-100)

On May 1, 2018, the Broncos signed local [undrafted free agent](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undrafted_free_agent) [running back](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Running_back) [Phillip Lindsay](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phillip_Lindsay), who became a fan favorite due to his underdog mentality, explosive play style and local roots.[\[100\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-m704-101) Lindsay became the first undrafted player in NFL history with 100+ scrimmage yards in each of their first two games[\[101\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-p732-102) and on December 18, 2018, Lindsay was voted to the [2019 Pro Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Pro_Bowl), making him the first undrafted offensive rookie in NFL history to be voted to a Pro Bowl.[\[102\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-103)

After getting off to a strong start, their [2018 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2018_Denver_Broncos_season) was up and down, eventually finishing with a 6–10 record and placing third in the [AFC West](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFC_West).[\[103\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-104) Coupled with the 5–11 season in [2017](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_Denver_Broncos_season), the Broncos had back-to-back losing seasons for the first time since [1971](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1971_Denver_Broncos_season)–[1972](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1972_Denver_Broncos_season).[\[104\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-105) Shortly after the conclusion of the regular season, head coach Vance Joseph was fired after recording a poor 11–21 record in two seasons.[\[105\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-106)

**Vic Fangio years (2019–2021)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=12)\]

On January 10, 2019, the Broncos hired [Chicago Bears](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chicago_Bears) defensive coordinator [Vic Fangio](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vic_Fangio) to become the 17th head coach in franchise history.[\[106\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-FangioBroncos-107) Fangio was chosen over [Mike Munchak](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Munchak), the Broncos' offensive line coach. Fangio received a four-year contract with a team option for an additional season.[\[107\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-108)

On February 13, 2019, [Joe Flacco](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joe_Flacco) was traded to the Broncos from the Baltimore Ravens.[\[108\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-y376-109) On October 6, 2019, the Broncos defeated the [Los Angeles Chargers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Los_Angeles_Chargers_season) for their 500th win, bringing their win–loss record to 500–432.[\[109\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-110)

On December 1, 2019, the Broncos started [Mizzou](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Missouri_Tigers_football) rookie quarterback [Drew Lock](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drew_Lock) for the first time.[\[110\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-n161-111) He led the Broncos to a 4–1 record to end the [2019 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_Denver_Broncos_season). The Broncos finished 2nd place in the AFC West Division at 7–9, missing the playoffs for a fourth consecutive year. In five games, Lock finished with 1,020 passing yards, seven touchdowns, and three interceptions.[\[111\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-112)

Due to the [COVID-19 pandemic](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/COVID-19_pandemic), the [2020 NFL season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_NFL_season) did not have a preseason or full training camps,[\[112\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-113) which likely contributed to an abnormally large amount of injuries that plagued the Broncos and other NFL teams. Star [linebacker](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linebacker) [Von Miller](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Von_Miller) suffered a season-ending ankle tendon injury before the regular season started, and starting [wide receiver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wide_receiver) [Courtland Sutton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Courtland_Sutton) suffered a season-ending torn [ACL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anterior_cruciate_ligament) during a week two game.[\[113\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-p262-114)[\[114\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-j818-115)

On November 29, 2020, after all three of the Broncos' [quarterbacks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quarterbacks) were placed in COVID-19 protocol, the Broncos were forced to turn to undrafted wide receiver and former college quarterback [Kendall Hinton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kendall_Hinton) as the emergency quarterback.[\[115\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-g298-116)[\[116\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-t128-117) Hinton completed only one pass for 13 yards in 9 attempts—the fewest pass completions in a single game in franchise history—and was intercepted twice. The Broncos' only scoring play was a 58-yard field goal by [placekicker](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Placekicker) [Brandon McManus](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandon_McManus) in a 31–3 loss to the [New Orleans Saints](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_New_Orleans_Saints_season). In July 2021, the [Pro Football Hall of Fame](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pro_Football_Hall_of_Fame) announced that Hinton's quarterback wristband would be added to the Hall of Fame as part of a display.[\[117\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-118)

The Broncos finished the 2020 season with a record of 5–11, last in the [AFC West](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFC_West), and missed the playoffs for the fifth consecutive year.[\[118\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-h689-119)

Following another season of uninspiring [quarterback](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quarterback) performances, the Broncos were the subject of multiple quarterback trade rumors during the 2021 offseason. [Aaron Rodgers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Aaron_Rodgers) and [Deshaun Watson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deshaun_Watson) were two names rumored to be of interest for the Broncos, but ultimately the Broncos traded for quarterback [Teddy Bridgewater](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teddy_Bridgewater) on April 28, 2021\. Bridgewater won the subsequent quarterback competition between himself and Drew Lock during the preseason, and he was named the Broncos' starting quarterback on August 25, 2021\.[\[119\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-h258-120)

The Broncos also made notable improvements in the [defensive secondary](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Defensive_back), signing former All-Pro [cornerback](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cornerback) [Kyle Fuller](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyle_Fuller) and cornerback [Ronald Darby](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ronald_Darby), as well as drafting [Alabama](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alabama_Crimson_Tide_football) cornerback [Patrick Surtain II](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Patrick_Surtain_II) with the ninth overall pick in the [2021 NFL draft](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021_NFL_draft). [Running back](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Running_back) [Phillip Lindsay](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Phillip_Lindsay) was replaced by [UNC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Carolina_Tar_Heels_football) rookie running back [Javonte Williams](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Javonte_Williams), who was drafted in the second round of the [2021 NFL draft](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021_NFL_draft) by the Broncos.[\[120\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-121)

On October 31, 2021, [Peyton Manning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peyton_Manning) (who won two AFC Championships, [Super Bowl 50](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_50), and an [NFL MVP](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League_Most_Valuable_Player_Award) during his four seasons as a Bronco) was inducted to the Broncos' [Ring of Fame](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos_Ring_of_Fame) during a game against [Washington](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_Commanders).[\[121\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-122)

On November 1, 2021, the Broncos traded franchise legend Von Miller to the [Los Angeles Rams](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_Angeles_Rams) in exchange for a 2nd and 3rd round pick in the [2022 NFL draft](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_NFL_draft).[\[122\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-123) At the time of the trade, Miller was the longest-tenured Bronco on the team, and the only remaining non-special teams player from Denver's Super Bowl 50 roster.[\[123\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-b591-124)

After another mediocre performance in the [2021 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021_Denver_Broncos_season) with the Broncos going 7–10, head coach Vic Fangio was dismissed on January 8, 2022, after losing to the [Kansas City Chiefs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021_Kansas_City_Chiefs_season).[\[124\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-125)

**Walton–Penner era (2022–present)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=13)\]

**Nathaniel Hackett season (2022)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=14)\]

The Broncos announced the hiring of [Green Bay Packers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Bay_Packers) offensive coordinator [Nathaniel Hackett](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nathaniel_Hackett) as head coach on January 27, 2022\.[\[125\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-126)

The Broncos then announced on February 1, 2022, that they were now up for sale and that they would be parting ways with the Bowlen family, the former owners of the franchise.[\[126\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-127)

Hackett's first hire as head coach was [Justin Outten](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justin_Outten) as offensive coordinator. He was hired on February 2, 2022\.[\[127\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-k405-128)

On March 16, 2022, the Broncos traded [Drew Lock](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Drew_Lock), [Noah Fant](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noah_Fant), [Shelby Harris](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shelby_Harris), Denver's 2022 first-round pick (No. 9), its 2022 second-round pick (No. 40), its 2023 first- and second-round picks, and its 2022 fifth-round pick for [Russell Wilson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Russell_Wilson) and the [Seattle Seahawks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seattle_Seahawks)' 2022 fourth-round pick.[\[128\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-129)

On June 7, 2022, the Broncos announced that a consortium led by former [Walmart](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Walmart) chairman [Rob Walton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S._Robson_Walton) had entered in an agreement to acquire the Denver Broncos for $4.65 billion.[\[129\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-130)[\[130\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-131) The NFL approved the bid on August 10, 2022\. On that day, the members of Walton's partnership, known as the Walton-Penner Family Ownership Group, were introduced to the press. The group includes Rob Walton, his daughter [Carrie Walton Penner](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carrie_Walton_Penner), son-in-law and current Walmart chairman [Greg Penner](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Greg_Penner), Starbucks chairwoman [Mellody Hobson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mellody_Hobson), former Secretary of State [Condoleezza Rice](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Condoleezza_Rice), and Formula One driver [Lewis Hamilton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lewis_Hamilton).[\[131\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-132)[\[132\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-133) Walton delegated most of his authority to Penner, who became CEO and operating head of the franchise as well as the public face of the Walton-Penner Group. Penner is recognized as the team's controlling owner by the NFL, and represents the Broncos at league meetings.[\[133\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-PennerBroncosCEO-134)[\[134\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-135)

On December 26, with the Broncos sitting at 4–11 following a 51–14 [Christmas Day](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League_Christmas_games) loss to the [Los Angeles Rams](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2022_Los_Angeles_Rams), Hackett was fired and replaced by interim head coach [Jerry Rosburg](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerry_Rosburg).[\[135\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-u741-136)[\[136\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-q995-137) Hackett became the fifth head coach to not finish his first season after [Lou Holtz](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lou_Holtz) in [1976](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1976_New_York_Jets_season), [Pete McCulley](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pete_McCulley) in [1978](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1978_San_Francisco_49ers_season), [Bobby Petrino](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bobby_Petrino) in [2007](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2007_Atlanta_Falcons_season), and [Urban Meyer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Urban_Meyer) in [2021](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2021_Jacksonville_Jaguars_season).[\[137\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-p486-138)

**Sean Payton years (2023–present)**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=15)\]

On January 31, 2023, [Sean Payton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sean_Payton) reported that he had accepted the head coaching job for the Denver Broncos, and he was officially hired as head coach for the [2023 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_Denver_Broncos_season) three days later.[\[138\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-139)

The Broncos started the season off 1–5, including a 20–70 loss to the [Miami Dolphins](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_Miami_Dolphins_season) in week 3\.[\[139\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-140) However, after a 21–31 loss to the [New York Jets](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_New_York_Jets_season), the team rallied off five straight wins, including victories over the [Buffalo Bills](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_Buffalo_Bills_season), [Green Bay Packers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_Green_Bay_Packers_season), and [Kansas City Chiefs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_Kansas_City_Chiefs_season); their first win against the Chiefs since 2015,[\[140\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-141) to get to 6–5. After a loss to the [Houston Texans](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_Houston_Texans_season) and a victory over the [Los Angeles Chargers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_Los_Angeles_Chargers_season), the Broncos won just one of their final four games, including a 23–26 loss to the [New England Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_New_England_Patriots_season) at home on Christmas Eve. After the loss, reports surfaced about contract disputes between Russell Wilson and Broncos management over an injury clause, causing Wilson to be benched by the team the final two games of the season.[\[141\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-142) The Broncos finished the 2023 season 8–9, good enough for their best record since the [2016 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_Denver_Broncos_season). However, the team finished under .500 for the seventh consecutive season, and missed the playoffs for the eighth consecutive season.[\[142\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-143)

Following the season, the Broncos released Russell Wilson, taking on $85M in dead-cap money, the largest in NFL history.[\[143\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-144)[\[144\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-145)

On March 7, the Broncos released veteran safety [Justin Simmons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Justin_Simmons_\(American_football\)). Simmons was the longest tenured player on the Broncos following [Brandon McManus'](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandon_McManus) departure the previous offseason.[\[145\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-146)

On April 22, The Broncos unveiled a new set of uniforms known as the "Mile High Collection," which was the teams first uniform change since the [1997 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_Denver_Broncos_season). A throwback uniform also pays homage to the 1977 Orange Crush uniforms that feature the iconic royal blue "D" helmets.[\[146\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-147)

In the [2024 NFL draft](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_NFL_draft), the Broncos selected [Bo Nix](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bo_Nix) with the team's first-round pick to succeed Russell Wilson as the teams quarterback.[\[147\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-148) Nix was named the starter prior to the [2024 NFL season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_NFL_season), beating out [Zach Wilson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zach_Wilson) and [Jarrett Stidham](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jarrett_Stidham), and becoming the first Broncos quarterback since [John Elway](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Elway) in [1983](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1983_Denver_Broncos_season) to start week 1 of his rookie season.[\[148\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-149)

The Broncos started the season 0–2, before winning five of their next six games to get to 5–3. After back-to-back losses against the [Baltimore Ravens](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_Baltimore_Ravens_season) and [Kansas City Chiefs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_Kansas_City_Chiefs_season), the team won four straight games to improve to 9–5, marking an improvement over their 8-win campaign the previous season. Despite back-to-back losses to the [Los Angeles Chargers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_Los_Angeles_Chargers_season) and [Cincinnati Bengals](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_Cincinnati_Bengals_season), the Broncos would defeat the Kansas City Chiefs in week 18 to finish the season with a record of 10–7, their first 10-win season since [2015](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_Denver_Broncos_season), and the teams first winning season since 2016\. With the victory, the Broncos clinched a playoff spot for the first time since winning [Super Bowl 50](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_50).[\[149\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-150)[\[150\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-151) In the [Wild Card Round](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024%E2%80%9325_NFL_playoffs) of the NFL playoffs, the Broncos lost to the [Buffalo Bills](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_Buffalo_Bills_season) 7–31.[\[151\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-152)

**Rivalries**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=16)\]

**Divisional**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=17)\]

*See also: [American Football League](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_League)*

The Denver Broncos have three [AFC West](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFC_West) rivals-the [Kansas City Chiefs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kansas_City_Chiefs), [Las Vegas Raiders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Las_Vegas_Raiders), and [Los Angeles Chargers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_Angeles_Chargers). All teams, along with the Broncos, were charter members of the [American Football League](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_League) (AFL), with each team placed in the AFL Western Division, forerunner of today's AFC West. The four teams have played each other twice a year for over 60 years, making the entire division one huge rivalry. The Broncos were barely competitive during the AFL years (1960–69), going a combined 10–49–1 against the Chiefs, Raiders, and Chargers.

**Kansas City Chiefs**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=18)\]

*Further information: [Broncos–Chiefs rivalry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broncos%E2%80%93Chiefs_rivalry)*

The Broncos have had several memorable matchups with the Chiefs, particularly during the years in which [John Elway](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Elway) was the Broncos' starting [quarterback](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_starting_quarterbacks) (1983–98). The Broncos defeated the Chiefs at [Arrowhead Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arrowhead_Stadium) in the divisional round of the [1997 NFL playoffs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997%E2%80%9398_NFL_playoffs), en route to their first [Super Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXII) victory. As of the [2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_NFL_season) season, the Chiefs hold a 73–57 series lead over the Broncos, including the aforementioned 1997 divisional playoff game.[\[152\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-153)

**Las Vegas Raiders**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=19)\]

*Further information: [Broncos–Raiders rivalry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broncos%E2%80%93Raiders_rivalry)*

Historically, the most heated divisional matchup for Denver is with the Raiders. The rivalry was ignited in its present form in [1977](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1977_NFL_season), when the Broncos advanced to their first [Super Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XII) by defeating the defending champion Raiders in the [1977 AFC Championship](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1977%E2%80%9378_NFL_playoffs).[\[153\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-154) The rivalry intensified in the mid-1990s, when [Mike Shanahan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Shanahan) was hired as the Broncos' [head coach](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_head_coaches) in [1995](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1995_Denver_Broncos_season). Shanahan coached the Raiders in [1988](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1988_NFL_season) before being fired four games into the [1989](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989_NFL_season) season. As of the [2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_NFL_season) season, the Raiders hold a 73–56–2 series lead over the Broncos, including 1–1 in the playoffs.[\[154\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-155)

**Los Angeles Chargers**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=20)\]

*Further information: [Broncos–Chargers rivalry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broncos%E2%80%93Chargers_rivalry)*

Unlike their record against the Chiefs and Raiders, as of the 2024 season, the Broncos have a winning record against the Chargers, with a 73–57–1 series lead, including 1–0 in the playoffs.[\[155\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-156) The Broncos pulled off one of the largest comebacks in [*Monday Night Football*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monday_Night_Football) history, when [Peyton Manning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peyton_Manning) led the Broncos from a 24–0 halftime deficit to a 35–24 win at [San Diego](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Diego)'s [Qualcomm Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qualcomm_Stadium) during the [2012](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_NFL_season) season. The two teams met in the playoffs for the first time on January 12, 2014, at [Denver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver)'s [Sports Authority Field at Mile High](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empower_Field_at_Mile_High), with the Broncos winning 24–17.[\[156\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-c686-157)

**Conference**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=21)\]

Aside from the aforementioned [AFC West](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFC_West) teams, the Broncos have had intra-conference rivalries over the years with the [Cleveland Browns](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleveland_Browns), [New England Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_England_Patriots), and [Pittsburgh Steelers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pittsburgh_Steelers).

**Cleveland Browns**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=22)\]

*See also: [The Drive (American football)](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Drive_\(American_football\)) and [The Fumble](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fumble)*

The Broncos had a brief rivalry with the Browns that arose from three [AFC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_Conference) championship matches in 1986, 1987 and 1989\. In the [1986 AFC Championship](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1986%E2%80%9387_NFL_playoffs#AFC_Championship:_Denver_Broncos_23,_Cleveland_Browns_20_\(OT\)), [quarterback](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_starting_quarterbacks) [John Elway](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Elway) led [*The Drive*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Drive_\(American_football\)) to secure a tie in the waning moments at [Cleveland Municipal Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cleveland_Municipal_Stadium); the Broncos went on to win in 23–20 in overtime.[\[157\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-158) One year later, the two teams met again in the [1987 AFC Championship](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1987%E2%80%9388_NFL_playoffs#AFC_Championship:_Denver_Broncos_38,_Cleveland_Browns_33) at [Mile High Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile_High_Stadium). Denver took a 21–3 lead, but Browns' quarterback [Bernie Kosar](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bernie_Kosar) threw four touchdown passes to tie the game at 31–31 halfway through the 4th quarter. After a long drive, John Elway threw a 20-yard touchdown pass to running back [Sammy Winder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sammy_Winder) to give Denver a 38–31 lead. Cleveland advanced to Denver's 8-yard line with 1:12 left, but Broncos' safety [Jeremiah Castille](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jeremiah_Castille) stripped Browns' running back [Earnest Byner](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earnest_Byner) of the football at the 2-yard line—a play that has been called [*The Fumble*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Fumble) by Browns' fans. The Broncos recovered it, gave Cleveland an intentional safety, and went on to win 38–33.[\[158\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-159) The two teams met yet again in the [1989 AFC Championship](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1989%E2%80%9390_NFL_playoffs#AFC_Championship:_Denver_Broncos_37,_Cleveland_Browns_21) at Mile High Stadium, which the Broncos easily won by a score of 37–21.[\[159\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-160) The Broncos did not win the Super Bowl after any of the championship games where they defeated the Browns, losing by an aggregate of 136–40. As of the [2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_NFL_season) season, the Broncos lead the all-time series 26–7.[\[160\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-161)

**New England Patriots**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=23)\]

*See also: [Broncos–Patriots rivalry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broncos%E2%80%93Patriots_rivalry) and [Tom Brady–Peyton Manning rivalry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Brady%E2%80%93Peyton_Manning_rivalry)*

The Broncos and Patriots met twice annually during the [American Football League](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_League) (AFL) years from 1960 to 1969, and played in the first-ever AFL game on September 9, 1960\.[\[161\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-162) Since [1995](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1995_NFL_season), the two teams have met frequently during the regular season, including nine consecutive seasons from 1995 to 2003\.[\[162\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-163) The teams' first playoff match on January 4, 1987, was John Elway's first career playoff win,[\[163\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-164) while the teams' second playoff match on January 14, 2006, game was the Broncos' first playoff win since Elway's retirement after the [1998 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1998_Denver_Broncos_season).[\[164\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-165) The game was also notable for [Champ Bailey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Champ_Bailey)'s 100-yard interception that resulted in a touchdown-saving tackle by [Benjamin Watson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Benjamin_Watson) at the 1-yard line.[\[165\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-166) On October 11, 2009, the two teams met with former Patriots' offensive coordinator, [Josh McDaniels](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josh_McDaniels) as the Broncos' [head coach](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_head_coaches). Both teams wore their AFL 50th anniversary jerseys.[\[166\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-167) The game featured a 98-yard drive in the fourth quarter, with a game-tying touchdown pass from [Kyle Orton](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kyle_Orton) to [Brandon Marshall](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandon_Marshall), followed by an overtime drive led by Orton that resulted in a 41-yard game-winning field goal by [Matt Prater](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matt_Prater).[\[167\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-168) The two teams met in the Divisional round of the [2011 playoffs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011%E2%80%9312_NFL_playoffs), with the Patriots blowing out [Tim Tebow](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tim_Tebow) and the Broncos by a score of 45–10.[\[63\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroncosPatriots2011-64) The Broncos' rivalry with the Patriots later intensified when longtime [Indianapolis Colts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indianapolis_Colts)' quarterback [Peyton Manning](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peyton_Manning) became the Broncos' starting quarterback from 2012 to 2015\. Manning and Patriots' quarterback [Tom Brady](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Brady) maintained a legendary [rivalry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Brady%E2%80%93Peyton_Manning_rivalry) from [2001](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2001_NFL_season)[\[168\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-169) until Manning's retirement after the [2015](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_NFL_season) season.[\[169\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-170) Though Brady dominated Manning in regular season play, winning nine of twelve meetings, Manning won three of five playoff meetings, including the Broncos' 26–16 win in the [2013 AFC Championship](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_AFC_Championship_Game) and the Broncos' 20–18 win in the [2015 AFC Championship](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015%E2%80%9316_NFL_playoffs#Conference_Championships).[\[170\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-AFCChampionship-171) As of the 2024 season, the Broncos lead the all-time series 31–24.[\[171\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-172)

**Pittsburgh Steelers**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=24)\]

*Further information: [Broncos–Steelers rivalry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broncos%E2%80%93Steelers_rivalry)*

As of the end of the 2024 season, the Broncos and Steelers have met in postseason play eight times, tied with five other pairings for the second–[most frequent playoff matchups](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_NFL_playoff_games#Most_frequent_matchups) in [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League) playoff history.[\[172\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-d494-173) The Broncos currently own a 5–3 playoff record vs. the Steelers.[\[173\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-174) Perhaps the most memorable postseason matchup occurred in the [1997 AFC Championship](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997%E2%80%9398_NFL_playoffs#AFC_Championship:_Denver_Broncos_24,_Pittsburgh_Steelers_21), in which the Broncos defeated the Steelers 24–21 at [Three Rivers Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three_Rivers_Stadium), en route to their first [Super Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXII) victory. Eight years later, the Steelers returned the favor at [INVESCO Field at Mile High](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empower_Field_at_Mile_High), defeating the Broncos 34–17 in the [2005 AFC Championship](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2005%E2%80%9306_NFL_playoffs#AFC_Championship:_Pittsburgh_Steelers_34,_Denver_Broncos_17), and subsequently won [Super Bowl XL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XL).[\[174\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-175) In the Wild Card round of the [2011 playoffs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011%E2%80%9312_NFL_playoffs), in a game dubbed *The 3:16 game*, the Broncos stunned the Steelers 29–23 on the first play of overtime, when quarterback Tim Tebow connected with [wide receiver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wide_receiver) [Demaryius Thomas](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Demaryius_Thomas) on an 80-yard game-winning touchdown pass.[\[175\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-176) The teams met again in the Divisional round of the [2015 playoffs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015%E2%80%9316_NFL_playoffs) at Denver, where the Broncos defeated the Steelers 23–16 on their way to a victory in [Super Bowl 50](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_50).[\[176\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-177) The Broncos lead the all-time series 20–14–1.[\[177\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-178)

**Historical**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=25)\]

**Seattle Seahawks**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=26)\]

*Main article: [Broncos–Seahawks rivalry](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Broncos%E2%80%93Seahawks_rivalry)*

The Broncos had an old rivalry with the [Seattle Seahawks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seattle_Seahawks), who were members of the [AFC West](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFC_West) from 1977 to 2001, prior to the Seahawks' move to the [NFC West](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NFC_West) as part of the [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League)'s [2002](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2002_NFL_season) re-alignment.[\[178\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-179) During the 25 years in which the Seahawks resided in the AFC West, the Broncos went 32–18 against the Seahawks, including a loss at Seattle in the [1983 NFL playoffs](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1983%E2%80%9384_NFL_playoffs). Since 2002, the Broncos have won three of five interconference meetings,[\[179\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-180) and the two teams met in [Super Bowl XLVIII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XLVIII) on February 2, 2014, with the Seahawks winning by a score of 43–8.[\[180\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-181) As of the [2024](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2024_NFL_season) season, the Broncos lead the all-time series 35–23.[\[181\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-182)

**Facilities**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=27)\]

![][image11]

[Mile High Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile_High_Stadium) was the home of the Broncos from 1960 to 2000

For most of their history, the Denver Broncos played in [Mile High Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile_High_Stadium). The [AFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_League) Broncos played at the [University of Denver](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/University_of_Denver)'s [Hilltop Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DU_Stadium) from time to time, including the first victory of an AFL team over an [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League) team: The Broncos beat the [Detroit Lions](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Detroit_Lions) on August 5, 1967, in a preseason game. The team has sold out every home game (including post-season games) since the [AFL–NFL merger](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/AFL%E2%80%93NFL_merger) in [1970](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1970_NFL_season), with the exception of two replacement games during the [1987](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1987_NFL_season) strike (but both were sold out before the strike).

During home games, the attendance is announced to the crowd, along with the number of no-shows (the fans subsequently boo the no shows). The fans are also known to chant "IN-COM-PLETE\!" every time the visiting team throws an [incomplete pass](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Forward_pass).[\[182\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-183) The stadium's legendary homefield advantage is regarded as one of the best in the NFL, especially during the playoffs. The Broncos had the best home record in pro football over a 32-year span from 1974 to 2006 (191–65–1). Mile High Stadium was one of the NFL's loudest stadiums, with steel flooring instead of [concrete](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Concrete), which may have given the Broncos an advantage over opponents, plus the advantage of altitude conditioning for the Broncos. In [2001](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2001_NFL_season), the team moved into then-named [Invesco Field at Mile High](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empower_Field_at_Mile_High), built next to the former site of the since-demolished Mile High Stadium. Sportswriter [Woody Paige](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Woody_Paige), along with many of Denver's fans, however, often refused to call the stadium by its full name, preferring to use "Mile High Stadium" because of its storied history and sentimental import. Additionally, [*The Denver Post*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Denver_Post) had an official policy of referring to the stadium as simply "Mile High Stadium" in protest, but dropped this policy in 2004\.[\[183\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-184)

![][image12]

[Empower Field at Mile High](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empower_Field_at_Mile_High) has been the Broncos' home since 2001

Prior to the [2011 season](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_Denver_Broncos_season), [Englewood](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Englewood,_Colorado)\-based [sporting goods](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sports_equipment) [retailer](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Retail) [Sports Authority](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sports_Authority) claimed the [naming rights](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Naming_rights) of Invesco Field, which became known as **Sports Authority Field at Mile High**.[\[184\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-185)[\[185\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-186) However, in the summer of 2016, Sports Authority went bankrupt, the stadium was renamed Broncos Stadium at Mile High, and the Broncos sought out a naming rights sponsor until September 2019 when they agreed to rename the stadium **Empower Field at Mile High**.[\[186\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-187)

The altitude has also been attributed as part of the team's home success. The stadium displays multiple references to the stadium's location of 5,280 feet (1.000 mi) above sea level, including a prominent mural just outside the visiting team's locker room. The team training facility, Broncos Park Powered by [CommonSpirit](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CommonSpirit_Health) (formerly known as the Paul D. Bowlen Memorial Broncos Centre), is a state-of-the-art facility located in [Dove Valley](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dove_Valley,_Colorado). With 13.5 acres (5.5 ha) of property, the facility hosts three full-size fields, a complete weight and training facility, and a cafeteria.[\[187\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-188)[\[188\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-189)

In their more than half-century of existence, the Broncos have never been shut out at home, a streak of over 400 games as of the [2016](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_NFL_season) season.[\[189\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-190)
