In late 2012, the Broncos announced that the stadium would receive $30 million upgrades including a new video board in the south end zone three times larger than the previous display. The renovations were finished before kickoff of the 2013 season.[\[190\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-191)

**Logos and uniforms**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=28)\]

**1968–1996**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=29)\]

![][image13]

Broncos logo (1997-present) and wordmark (1968-1996)

![][image14]

Denver Broncos uniform set from 1967 to 1996\. The logo was designed by Edwin Guy Taylor of Denver. A contest was held through Public Service of Denver to come up with a new logo for the team. Taylor's submission was selected late in 1967 and adopted the next season. The team briefly wore orange pants with the away jerseys between 1969 and 1971 and 1978–1979.

When the Broncos debuted in [1960](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1960_NFL_season), their original uniforms were said to have drawn as much attention as their play on the field. They featured white and mustard yellow jerseys, contrasting brown helmets, brown pants, and vertically striped socks. Two years later, the team unveiled a new logo featuring a bucking horse and changed their team colors to orange, royal blue and white. The [1962](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1962_NFL_season) uniform consisted of white pants, orange helmets, and either orange or white jerseys.[\[191\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-192)[\[192\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-193)

In [1968](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1968_NFL_season), the Broncos debuted a design that became known as "Orange Crush". Their logo was redesigned so that the horse was coming out of a "D". Additionally, the helmets were changed to royal blue, and the sleeves had thin stripes with other minor modifications added. From 1969 to 1971, and again from 1978 to 1979, the team wore orange pants with their white jerseys.[\[193\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-Endzone-194) In 1975, the face masks were changed to white from grey.

The Broncos wore their white jerseys at home throughout the [1971](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1971_NFL_season) season, as well as for [1980](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1980_NFL_season) home games against the [San Diego Chargers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Diego_Chargers) and [Dallas Cowboys](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dallas_Cowboys), the latter in hopes to bring out the "blue jersey jinx" which has followed the Cowboys for decades. (The Broncos won 41–20.) The Broncos wore their white jerseys for [1983](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1983_NFL_season) home games against the [Philadelphia Eagles](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philadelphia_Eagles), [Los Angeles Raiders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Los_Angeles_Raiders) and [Cincinnati Bengals](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cincinnati_Bengals), but did not wear white at home again for two decades — *see next section*.[\[193\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-Endzone-194)[\[194\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-195)

In [1994](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1994_NFL_season), in honor of the 75th anniversary season of the [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League), the Broncos wore their [1965](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1965_NFL_season) [throwback uniforms](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Throwback_uniforms) for two games—a Week 3 home game against the Raiders and a road game at the [Buffalo Bills](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Buffalo_Bills) the following week.[\[193\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-Endzone-194)

**1997–2011**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=30)\]

![][image15]

[Thunder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thunder_\(mascot\)) (mascot)

The Broncos radically changed their logo and uniforms in [1997](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1997_NFL_season), a design that the team used until 2023\. The new logos and uniforms were unveiled on February 4, 1997\.[\[195\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-196) Navy blue replaced royal blue on the team's color scheme. The current logo is a profile of a horse's head, with an orange mane and navy blue outlines.[\[196\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-2012UniformChange-197) The Broncos' popular live animal mascot [Thunder](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thunder_\(mascot\)) was the inspiration to incorporate a horse-head profile as part of the logo on the team's helmets.[\[197\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-Pomeroy-198) During a February 4, 1997, press conference introducing the new logo, the team president and the art director for [Nike](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nike,_Inc.), who were the creators of the new design, described it as "a powerful horse with a fiery eye and mane."[\[198\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-199)

The Broncos began wearing navy blue jerseys, replacing their longtime orange jerseys that had been the team's predominant home jersey color since 1962\. This new uniform design features a new word mark, numbering font and a streak that runs up and down the sides of both the jerseys and the pants. On the navy blue jerseys, the streak is orange, with an orange collar and white numerals trimmed in orange, while on the road white jerseys, the streak is navy blue, with a thin orange accent strip on both sides, a navy collar and navy numerals trimmed in orange; the helmet facemasks became navy blue. When they debuted, these uniforms were vilified by the press and fans, until the Broncos won their first-ever [Super Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXII) in the new design that same season. The navy blue jerseys served as the team's primary home jersey until the end of the [2011](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_NFL_season) season — *see next section*.[\[196\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-2012UniformChange-197)

In [2002](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2002_NFL_season), the Broncos introduced an alternate orange jersey that is a mirror image of the aforementioned navy blue jerseys, but with orange and navy trading places. Like the road white jerseys, the white pants with the navy blue streaks running down the sides are worn with this uniform. This jersey was used only once in the 2002 and [2004](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2004_NFL_season) seasons, and were used twice per season from 2008 to 2011\. [Mike Shanahan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Shanahan), the team's [head coach](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_head_coaches) from 1995 to 2008, was not a big fan of the alternate orange jerseys.[\[199\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-200) The Broncos previously wore orange jerseys as a throwback uniform in a [Thanksgiving Day](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NFL_on_Thanksgiving_Day) game at the [Dallas Cowboys](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dallas_Cowboys) in [2001](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2001_NFL_season).[\[200\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-201)

The team also introduced navy blue pants in [2003](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2003_NFL_season), with orange side streaks to match with the navy blue jerseys. Though they were part of the uniform change in 1997 (in fact, they were worn for a couple of 1997 preseason games) and most players wanted to wear them, the only player who vetoed wearing them was [John Elway](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Elway), thereby delaying their eventual introduction.[\[201\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-2003Uniforms-202) From 2003 to 2011, these pants were primarily used for select prime-time and late-season home games (excluding the [2008](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2008_NFL_season) season), and since [2012](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_NFL_season), are used exclusively with the now-alternate navy blue jerseys — *see next section*.

On November 16, 2003, the Broncos wore their white jerseys at home for the first time since [1983](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1983_NFL_season), in a game vs. the [San Diego Chargers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Diego_Chargers). This was compensation for a uniform mix-up, after the teams' first meeting at [San Diego](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/San_Diego)'s [Qualcomm Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qualcomm_Stadium) in Week 2 earlier that season, when the Chargers were the team that was supposed to declare their uniform color. The Chargers were planning to wear their white jerseys, but the visiting Broncos came to the stadium in white, and were fined [$](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dollar_sign)25,000 by the [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League) as a result. When the two teams met at [INVESCO Field at Mile High](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Empower_Field_at_Mile_High) later that season (Week 11), the NFL allowed the visiting Chargers to choose their uniform color in advance, and they chose navy blue, forcing the Broncos to wear their white jerseys at home.[\[201\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-2003Uniforms-202)

In [2009](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2009_NFL_season), in honor of their 50th anniversary season as one of the eight original [American Football League](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Football_League) teams, the Broncos wore their 1960 throwback uniforms (brown helmets, mustard yellow and brown jerseys) for games against two fellow AFL rivals—a Week 5 home game vs. the [New England Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_England_Patriots), as well as the following week at the San Diego Chargers.[\[202\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-legacy-203)[\[203\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-post-204)

**2012–2023**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=31)\]

![][image16]

The Denver Broncos uniform set from 2012 to 2023\.

Beginning in [2012](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2012_NFL_season), the orange jerseys that served as the alternate colored jerseys from 2002 to 2011 became the primary home jersey, while the navy blue jerseys that served as the primary home jersey from 1997 to 2011 switched to alternate designation.[\[204\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-y995-205) The change was made due to overwhelming popularity with the fans, who pressured the Broncos to return to orange as the team's primary home jersey color.[\[196\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-2012UniformChange-197) Since the 2012 uniform change, the team has worn the alternate navy blue jerseys for at least one home game per season, with the exception of [2013](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2013_NFL_season), in which the Broncos wore their alternate navy blue uniforms for an October 6, 2013, road game at the [Dallas Cowboys](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dallas_Cowboys), which the Broncos won in a shootout, 51–48.[\[205\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-206) The team will either wear the navy blue or the white pants – with the orange side stripes – to match with the alternate navy blue jerseys. The team initially did not wear the white pants with the orange side stripes, until a November 1, 2015, game vs. the [Green Bay Packers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Bay_Packers), in which the Broncos wore said design to match the uniform ensemble that was used during the team's [Super Bowl XXXII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXII) win over the Packers.[\[206\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-207) On October 30, 2022, the Broncos debuted a new combination of white jerseys and alternate navy blue pants in an [NFL London Game](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NFL_International_Series) at the [Jacksonville Jaguars](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacksonville_Jaguars), with mismatched side stripes of navy blue (white jersey) and orange (navy blue pants).[\[207\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-208)

As the designated home team in [Super Bowl 50](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_50), the Broncos – who have a 0–4 [Super Bowl](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Super_Bowl_champions) record when using their standard orange jerseys – chose to wear their white jerseys as the designated "home" team.[\[208\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-209)[\[209\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-210)

In [2016](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_NFL_season), the Broncos' unveiled a new [Color Rush](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NFL_Color_Rush) uniform, which the team wore for a [*Thursday Night*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thursday_Night_Football) game at the [San Diego Chargers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2016_San_Diego_Chargers_season) on October 13, 2016\. The uniform kit contained the following features: orange pants, which the team wore for the first time since 1979, orange socks and shoes, along with block-style numerals trimmed in navy blue that mirrored the team's 1968–1996 uniform style. Due to the [NFL](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Football_League)'s one-helmet rule implemented in 2013, the helmets remained the same, with the team temporarily replacing the modern primary logo with the throwback "D-horse" logo.[\[210\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-211) The same uniform was used for a Thursday night game against the [Indianapolis Colts](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_Indianapolis_Colts_season) during the [2017](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2017_NFL_season) season and again during a 2018 game against the [Pittsburgh Steelers](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pittsburgh_Steelers).[\[211\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-212) In a Week 2 game vs. the [Washington Commanders](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Washington_Commanders) in [2023](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_Denver_Broncos_season), the Broncos wore their white jerseys at home for the first time since [2003](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2003_Denver_Broncos_season), to honor the 25th anniversary of the [Super Bowl XXXIII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXIII) team.[\[212\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-213) In 2023, the Color Rush uniforms were paired with a white alternate helmet, again using the modernized "D-horse" logo,[\[213\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-214) and were discontinued at the end of that season, with the arrival of a new uniform kit in 2024—*see next section*.

**2024–present**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=32)\]

On April 22, 2024, the Broncos unveiled a simpler uniform design, eliminating the mismatched jersey and pant stripes that characterized their 1997 redesign and reverting to a more vintage block number style and letters inspired by the signage of [Colorado's national parks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_protected_areas_of_Colorado). The set consists of a primary home orange and road white uniform, and an alternate navy blue uniform; all uniforms could be worn with either orange, white or navy blue pants.[\[5\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroncosMileHighUnis-5) The striping on the uniform is a nod to the [Rocky Mountains](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rocky_Mountains). The primary helmets remain navy blue while the alternate remains white; both feature the current Broncos logo with triangle clusters on top to represent Denver's elevation. The Broncos also unveiled a throwback 1977 "Orange Crush" uniform along with the royal blue "D-horse" helmet; this is due to the NFL allowing teams with new uniforms to unveil a second alternate helmet this season.[\[5\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroncosMileHighUnis-5)[\[6\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-ShookBroncosUnis2024-6)[\[214\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-215)[\[215\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-216)

**In the media and popular culture**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=46)\]

* Tim McKernan, a.k.a. [Barrel Man](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_Man_\(Denver_Broncos\)), began wearing a barrel in 1977 after making a $10 (equivalent to $50 in 2024\) bet with his brother, Scott, that by wearing one he could get on television. McKernan won the bet, and the barrel he had painted to look like an [Orange Crush](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orange_Crush) soda can became his signature costume, and resulted in him becoming one of the Broncos' most recognized fans and a popular mascot. McKernan died on December 5, 2009\.[\[227\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-228)  
* The animated television show [*South Park*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/South_Park), set in [Park County](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Park_County,_Colorado), often mentions the Denver Broncos; show creators [Trey Parker](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trey_Parker) and [Matt Stone](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matt_Stone) both grew up in Colorado as devout Broncos fans.[\[228\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-229)  
* In [*The Simpsons*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Simpsons) season 5 episode [Cape Feare](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cape_Feare), when the family are to be given new identities, Homer imagines himself as John Elway, scoring a (consolation) touchdown against San Francisco. Conversely, in the 1996 episode "[You Only Move Twice](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/You_Only_Move_Twice)", Hank Scorpio gives Homer Simpson the Denver Broncos as a thank-you gift for helping him. However, Homer complains that he wanted to own the [Dallas Cowboys](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dallas_Cowboys), as the Broncos team that just arrived are playing very sloppy football on his front lawn (a reference to the team losing four Super Bowl appearances, three by significant margins including [Super Bowl XII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XII) against Dallas). Incidentally, the Broncos were 13–3 in the 1996 season, and won the Super Bowl the next two seasons. Only two seasons later in the Super Bowl-centric episode "[Sunday, Cruddy Sunday](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sunday,_Cruddy_Sunday)", Homer chooses Denver as his [Super Bowl XXXIII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XXXIII) pick over Moe's choice of the [Atlanta Falcons](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Atlanta_Falcons). In the episode, "[The Bonfire of the Manatees](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Bonfire_of_the_Manatees)", Homer picks the Broncos to win the Super Bowl over the [Seattle Seahawks](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seattle_Seahawks). The two teams later did play against each other in [Super Bowl XLVIII](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Super_Bowl_XLVIII) which aired on [Fox](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fox_Broadcasting_Company), the U.S. home of *The Simpsons*; but the result was a Seahawks victory instead.  
* In the 1979 [*Mork & Mindy*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mork_%26_Mindy) episode "Hold That Mork", Mork's character, played by [Robin Williams](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robin_Williams), became the first male [cheerleader in Broncos' history](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos_Cheerleaders). As a member of the "Pony Express", he trotted out on the field at [Mile High Stadium](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mile_High_Stadium) during an actual Broncos' game vs. the [New England Patriots](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/New_England_Patriots) on November 11, 1979\. The episode aired exactly two weeks later.[\[229\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-230)  
* Many former Broncos are now in broadcasting, including [Shannon Sharpe](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shannon_Sharpe), [Mark Schlereth](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mark_Schlereth), [Alfred Williams](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alfred_Williams), [Tom Jackson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tom_Jackson_\(American_football,_born_1951\)), [Ed McCaffrey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed_McCaffrey), [Brian Griese](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Griese), [David Diaz-Infante](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Diaz-Infante), [Terrell Davis](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Terrell_Davis) and [Brandon Stokley](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brandon_Stokley). Some former Broncos work in radio, [KKFN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KKFN) and [KDFD](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KDFD) in Denver, Colorado.  
* Former tight end and wide receiver [Nate Jackson](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nate_Jackson) has written and published two nonfiction books, *Slow Getting Up*[\[230\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-231) and *Fantasy Man*.[\[231\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-232) His writing about the NFL has appeared in [*Slate*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Slate_\(magazine\)),[\[232\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-slate-nj-233) [*Deadspin*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deadspin),[\[233\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-234) [*The Daily Beast*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Daily_Beast),[\[234\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-dailybeast-nj-235) [*The New York Times*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_New_York_Times),[\[235\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-NYT-nj-236) [*The Wall Street Journal*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wall_Street_Journal),[\[236\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-wsj-nj-237) and [*BuzzFeed*](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/BuzzFeed),[\[237\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-238) among others. Jackson also co-hosts the *Caveman Poet Society*.[\[238\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-239)

**Radio and television**\[[edit](https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Denver_Broncos&action=edit&section=47)\]

*Main article: [List of Denver Broncos broadcasters](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_Denver_Broncos_broadcasters)*

The Broncos' flagship radio station is currently [KOA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KOA_\(AM\)), 850AM, a 50,000-watt station owned by [iHeartMedia](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/IHeartMedia).[\[239\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-u663-240) [Dave Logan](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dave_Logan_\(American_football\)) is the play-by-play announcer, with former Broncos' wide receiver [Ed McCaffrey](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ed_McCaffrey) serving as the color commentator beginning in 2012, replacing [Brian Griese](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brian_Griese).[\[240\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-241) Ed McCaffrey was replaced by Rick Lewis. Until 2010, preseason games not selected for airing on national television were shown on [KCNC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KCNC-TV), channel 4, which is a [CBS](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CBS) [owned-and-operated station](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Owned-and-operated_station), as well as other CBS affiliates around the [Rocky Mountain](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rocky_Mountain) region. On May 26, 2011, the Broncos announced that [KUSA](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KUSA-TV) channel 9, an [NBC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NBC) affiliate also known as **9NEWS** in the Rocky Mountain region, will be the team's new television partner for preseason games.[\[241\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroadcastPartners-242)

In 2011, the Broncos began a partnership with [KJMN](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KJMN), 92.1 FM, a leading [Spanish language](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spanish_language) radio station owned by [Entravision Communications](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Entravision) (EVC). The partnership also includes broadcasting rights for a half-hour weekly TV show on [KCEC](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/KCEC_\(TV\)), the local [Univision](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Univision) affiliate operated by EVC.[\[241\]](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Denver_Broncos#cite_note-BroadcastPartners-242)
